    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA154-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu iravukkuṟit talaivaṉ ciṟaippuṟamāka (ET: tōḻi) varaivu (G1+2: varavu) kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how marriage was asked for while HE was behind the fence during the night tryst.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA154">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kāṉamuṅ kammeṉ ṟaṉṟē vāṉamum</l>
<l>            varaikiḻip paṉṉa maiyiruḷ parappip</l>
<l>            palkura leḻili pāṭō vātē</l>
<l>            mañcutava ḻiṟumpiṟ kaḷiṟuvalam paṭutta</l>
<l>            veñciṉa vuḻuvaip pēḻvā yēṟṟai </l>
<l>            yañcuttaka vuraṟu mōcai kēḷātu</l>
<l>            tuñcuti yōvila tūvi lāṭṭi</l>
<l>            pērañar poruta pukarpaṭu neñca</l>
<l>            nīraṭu neruppiṟ ṟaṇiya viṉṟavar</l>
<l>            vārā rāyiṉō naṉṟē cāral </l>
<l>            vilaṅkumalai yārā ṟuḷḷutoṟu</l>
<l>            nilamparan toḻukumeṉ ṉiṟaiyi ṉeñcē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The forest is silent(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kam</term> is one of the rarer ideophones. T.V.G. ascertains that it denotes silence, but one would want to look for parallels.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">and in the sky</l>
<l>the many-voiced clouds do not stop singing,</l>
<l rend="indent">having spread kajal darkness, as if to split the mountain.</l>
<l>Can you sleep, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">without hearing the fearful roaring sound</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the vast-mouthed male of the tiger in hot anger</l>
<l rend="indent3">that had brought on the strength(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">valam paṭutta</term>: T.V.G. reads here once more the topos of the elephant having been made to fall dead on the right side (if it falls on the left side the tiger will not eat it). Taken as above, however, the phrase does not seem to make clear whether there actually has been a victor in the fight nor who it might have been (in any case a roaring tiger is not dead).</note> of the elephant-bull</l>
<l rend="indent4">in a cloud-covered thicket?</l>
<l>If he won't come today,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that, like fire is killed by water, [my] stained(?)<note place="foot">What is the association of <term xml:lang="ta">pukarpaṭu</term> (suffering spots) in connection with the grieved heart?</note> heart is appeased, 	</l>
<l>struck by the great grief of a woman in the pure house,</l>
<l rend="indent3">it [is] good.</l>
<l>My unchecked heart flows, spreading on the ground,<note place="foot">I suggest to read an elliptical metaphor here: in the grief of her heart, the tears she spills become a flood that spreads on the ground, a fairly familiar motif.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">whenever I remember [his] difficult path on the slopy transverse</l>
<l rend="indent3">mountain.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
